On September 11, 2018, President Donald Trump delivered remarks at the Flight 93 National Memorial in Shanksville, Pennsylvania, to honor the memory of the nearly 3,000 people who lost their lives in the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001. The President paid tribute to the 40 passengers and crew members of Flight 93 who rose up against the hijackers and changed the course of history. He emphasized the bravery and sacrifice of these individuals and the impact they had in saving lives and preventing a devastating attack on the United States Capitol. The President also expressed gratitude to the first responders, law enforcement, and military personnel who protect the nation. He highlighted the resolve of America to never submit to tyranny and to continue fighting against terrorism. The President concluded by dedicating the Tower of Voices, a structure that holds 40 chimes to honor the passengers and crew members of Flight 93, symbolizing their courage and love. He emphasized that America's future is written by heroes who rise up in times of need. The President's remarks were a solemn tribute to the victims of 9/11 and a reminder of the resilience and strength of the American spirit.